snippet.textDisplay:
Shame this was a TV movie and not theatrical, as this song would've gotten so much attention. This song pretty much embodies the feelings of Millennials and Zoomers in regards to how the people in charge are treating the planet and society as a whole. Eventually they'll be in charge, but if the people currently in charge don't stop, there won't be anything to take charge of, because they don't learn from history. This movie was aimed at the youngest Zoomers (as Generation Alpha are still like 5 years old max at the moment), so it makes sense they did this. But the fact they can also make it relate to Millennial's feelings, when we're in our 20s/30s is impressive.

A lot of lines in this really hit hard, like "Silence is still taking sides" which to me, is what a lot of politicians do to avoid addressing big things, and cause more problems. A recent situation was Tulsi Gabbard saying "Present" on the impeachment trials of Trump. She may think she was "standing up" but she was taking a side, without taking a side. I'd rather disagree with someone than see someone stand by and not take action, especially if they're someone put into power.

"History Changes but We Lost the Pages" also hit hard, as recently my county has started doing things like removing statues of people who were not the best people, but still had an impact in history. By trying to erase them, you aren't just trying to erase the bad they did, but also the good, as well as the lessons that people learned FROM them. Christopher Columbus is a good example of this. Yes, he helped aid in the massacre of Native Americans, but without him, the USA wouldn't exist. (This is coming from someone who is half-Native American, btw) If you erase him, sure, the USA will still exist, but people in the future might forget how bad it is to judge someone based on being unknown, a different race, etc.

"The world has gone crazy and no one seems to listen" is another one, big with Climate Change right now. Millennials and Zoomers are pushing for governments to take Climate Change serious, but almost none of them are.

"History Changes but We Lost the Pages" also hit hard, as recently my county has started doing things like removing statues of people who were not the best people, but still had an impact in history. By trying to erase them, you aren't just trying to erase the bad they did, but also the good, as well as the lessons that people learned FROM them. Christopher Columbus is a good example of this. Yes, he helped aid in the massacre of Native Americans, but without him, the USA wouldn't exist. (This is coming from someone who is half-Native American, btw) If you erase him, sure, the USA will still exist, but people in the future might forget how bad it is to judge someone based on being unknown, a different race, etc.

"The world has gone crazy and no one seems to listen" is another one, big with Climate Change right now. Millennials and Zoomers are pushing for governments to take Climate Change serious, but almost none of them are.
